Some 10,000 people gathered in Warsaw's Pilsudski  Square mid-afternoon Friday for a rally organised by the Solidarity union,  demonstrating against the Waldemar Pawlak government, police sources said.
Demonstrators, carrying Solidarity Flags, held up banners saying "Down  with Unemployment," "Down with Wage Controls" and "Enough with Energy Price  Rises."
They chanted "Down with the Communists".
After gathering in Pilsudski Square, the demonstrators were to process to  the parliament and then the government building to present a list of demands.
They called for a reduction in the working week from 42 to 40 hours, the  application of an "enterprise pact" promoted by the previous government, tax  reform to help people with large families and guarantees of help for the  disadvantaged.
